{layout 'layouts/landing.latte'}

{block content}
<main class="landing">
    {* ─── 1. Hero ─── *}
    <section class="hero" id="hero">
        <div class="hero-grid">
            <div class="hero-content">
                <div class="hero-brand">
                    <span class="hero-brand-mark" aria-hidden="true">金</span>
                    <span class="hero-brand-text">Kintsugi</span>
                </div>
                <h1 class="hero-tagline">
                    Mend the wallet. <span class="accent">Keep the gold.</span>
                </h1>
                <p class="hero-sub">
                    {$leafDescription ?? 'Atomic, sweeper-proof wallet rescue using EIP-7702.'}
                    Open source. Runs locally. No fees, ever.
                </p>
                <div class="hero-cta-row">
                    <div class="install-box code-block-wrapper">
                        <span class="prompt">$</span>
                        <code id="install-cmd">npm install -g @kintsugi/cli</code>
                        <button type="button" class="copy-btn" aria-label="Copy install command" onclick="
                            navigator.clipboard.writeText('npm install -g @kintsugi/cli');
                            this.classList.add('copied');
                            setTimeout(() => this.classList.remove('copied'), 1400);
                        ">
                            <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor"><path d="M8 2a2 2 0 00-2 2v9a2 2 0 002 2h7a2 2 0 002-2V4a2 2 0 00-2-2H8zm-4 5a2 2 0 00-2 2v9a2 2 0 002 2h7a2 2 0 002-2v-1H8a3 3 0 01-3-3V7H4z"/></svg>
                        </button>
                    </div>
                    <a href="{$leafBaseUrl}/getting-started/install/" class="btn-secondary">
                        Read the docs
                        <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10.293 3.293a1 1 0 011.414 0l6 6a1 1 0 010 1.414l-6 6a1 1 0 01-1.414-1.414L14.586 11H3a1 1 0 110-2h11.586l-4.293-4.293a1 1 0 010-1.414z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
                    </a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    {* ─── 2. The hostage problem ─── *}
    <section class="problem-section" id="problem">
        <div class="problem-grid">
            <div>
                <span class="section-eyebrow">The problem</span>
                <h2 class="section-title">Your keys are leaked. Your wallet is being watched.</h2>
                <p class="section-lede">
                    A sweeper bot now monitors the compromised address around the clock. The moment any ETH lands there to pay gas for a recovery transaction, the bot front-runs you and drains it in the same block. Tokens, NFTs, and ENS names sit visible but unreachable. Most rescues fail before they start.
                </p>
                <p style="color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.9375rem; line-height: 1.65;">
                    Kintsugi removes the gas dependency entirely. The victim wallet never holds ETH at any point. A separate rescuer wallet pays for and submits the recovery in one atomic Type-4 transaction, transferring every selected asset out before the sweeper sees an opening.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div>
                <div class="tx-graph" aria-label="Sweeper bot drains incoming gas">
                    <div class="row">
                        <span class="label">Block N</span>
                        <span><span class="actor-victim">victim ←</span> 0.01 ETH <span class="arrow">from your wallet</span></span>
                        <span style="color: oklch(0.6 0.012 60);">+10⁻²</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="row">
                        <span class="label">Block N</span>
                        <span><span class="actor-sweeper">sweeper →</span> 0.01 ETH <span class="arrow">to attacker</span></span>
                        <span class="amount-drained">drained</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="row">
                        <span class="label">Block N+1</span>
                        <span>your rescue tx <span class="arrow">→ reverted</span></span>
                        <span class="amount-drained">no gas</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="row" style="border-top: 1px solid oklch(0.35 0.012 60); margin-top: 0.5rem; padding-top: 0.75rem;">
                        <span class="label">Result</span>
                        <span>tokens, NFTs, ENS still on the compromised wallet</span>
                        <span class="amount-left">stranded</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    {* ─── 3. What sweepers ignore ─── *}
    <section class="landing-section" id="coverage">
        <span class="section-eyebrow">The recovery gap</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">They take what's liquid. They leave what's yours.</h2>
        <p class="section-lede">
            Drainer bots optimize for fast liquidation. They sweep ETH and the most liquid ERC-20s, ignore everything that takes effort to fence, and move on. The leftovers are often the most personally valuable holdings, but a working sweeper still blocks any normal recovery attempt.
        </p>
        <div class="cards-row">
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-card-icon" aria-hidden="true">字</div>
                <h3>ENS names</h3>
                <p>
                    Your dot-eth identity, the one you've used everywhere for years, is rarely auto-drained. It's also typically the hardest to move once a sweeper is watching. Kintsugi handles unwrapped 2LDs, wrapped names, and subdomains in a single batch.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-card-icon" aria-hidden="true">画</div>
                <h3>Illiquid NFTs</h3>
                <p>
                    Long-tail collections, art, in-game items, memberships. Bots usually skip ERC-721 and ERC-1155 because the resale path is slow. They stay on the compromised wallet, visible to everyone, recoverable by no one.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-card-icon" aria-hidden="true">小</div>
                <h3>Low-cap tokens</h3>
                <p>
                    Reward tokens, governance positions, vested allocations, anything without a liquid pool. Drainers ignore them, but you still cannot reach them through a wallet the sweeper is gating.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <div class="divider-rule"></div>

    {* ─── 4. How Kintsugi works ─── *}
    <section class="landing-section landing-section-narrow" id="how">
        <span class="section-eyebrow">How it works</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">One transaction. No gas from you. Nothing left behind.</h2>
        <p class="section-lede">
            EIP-7702 lets a victim wallet temporarily delegate execution to a battle-tested rescue contract. Combined with EIP-712 batch authorization, every selected asset moves to your safe wallet inside one atomic Type-4 transaction, paid for by a separate rescuer key.
        </p>
        <div class="steps-row">
            <div class="step-card">
                <span class="step-num">1</span>
                <h3>You sign locally</h3>
                <p>
                    The CLI signs an EIP-7702 authorization plus an EIP-712 batch of transfers (ERC-20, NFTs, ENS). Nothing leaves your machine yet. The victim private key is held in memory only and never written to disk.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="step-card">
                <span class="step-num">2</span>
                <h3>Rescuer submits</h3>
                <p>
                    A separate rescuer wallet you control submits a single Type-4 transaction. It pays the gas, attaches your authorization, and calls the audited rescue contract on your behalf. Your wallet's ETH balance never rises above zero.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="step-card">
                <span class="step-num">3</span>
                <h3>Assets land safely</h3>
                <p>
                    Inside the same transaction, the contract executes every transfer to a fresh safe address you control. The sweeper sees the rescue land, finds nothing to grab, and moves on. The victim wallet is then optionally revoked back to a pure EOA.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="callout">
            The victim wallet's balance never rises above zero. There is no opening for a sweeper to act on, because there is nothing to take.
        </div>
    </section>

    {* ─── 5. UI / CLI showcase ─── *}
    <section class="landing-section" id="try">
        <span class="section-eyebrow">Two ways in</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">A guided UI for panic. A pure CLI for power.</h2>
        <p class="section-lede">
            Same atomic flow under the hood, two surfaces to drive it. The web UI is launched from the CLI as a localhost server. The browser only sees session-bound addresses and signatures. Private keys never leave the local Node process.
        </p>
        <div class="showcase-grid">
            <div class="showcase-card">
                <div class="preview">
                    <img src="{$leafBaseUrl}/assets/images/ui/welcome.png" alt="Kintsugi web UI welcome screen showing the Kintsugi wordmark and Mend the wallet, Keep the gold tagline" loading="lazy" width="1440" height="900">
                </div>
                <div class="body">
                    <h3>The web UI</h3>
                    <p>
                        Start with <code>kintsugi ui</code> and a localhost browser tab walks you through five steps: network, wallets, discovery, plan, submit. Friendly for someone in panic mode.
                    </p>
                    <a href="{$leafBaseUrl}/ui-walkthrough/network/">Walk through the UI</a>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="showcase-card">
                <div class="preview">
                    <pre class="preview-terminal"><span class="comment"># launch the guided localhost UI</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> kintsugi ui

<span class="comment"># ...or do everything in the terminal</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> kintsugi rescue

<span class="comment"># inspect a wallet read-only first</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> kintsugi status 0xVictim...

<span class="comment"># after rescue, optionally clear delegation</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> kintsugi revoke</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="body">
                    <h3>The CLI</h3>
                    <p>
                        The same end-to-end rescue, fully scriptable. Inspect wallets, run interactive rescues, revoke delegation. Pipes well, no browser required.
                    </p>
                    <a href="{$leafBaseUrl}/cli-reference/rescue/">Read the CLI reference</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    {* ─── 5.5 Agent skill banner ─── *}
    <section class="landing-section landing-section-narrow agent-banner" id="agent">
        <div class="agent-banner-grid">
            <div>
                <span class="section-eyebrow">Or just ask your agent</span>
                <h2 class="section-title agent-banner-title">In panic? Don't read. <span class="accent">Ask.</span></h2>
                <p class="section-lede agent-banner-lede">
                    Kintsugi ships a free agent skill following the <a href="https://agentskills.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">agentskills.io</a> spec. Install it once and Claude Code, Cursor, Codex, Cline, Gemini CLI, or any compatible agent will drive the entire flow for you in plain English.
                </p>
                <p class="agent-banner-prompt-label">Then just paste this and let it walk you through:</p>
                <div class="agent-prompt code-block-wrapper">
                    <span class="agent-prompt-quote" aria-hidden="true">"</span>
                    <p class="agent-prompt-text" id="agent-prompt-text">My wallet got drained but I have hostage assets there. Help me rescue them with Kintsugi.</p>
                    <button type="button" class="copy-btn agent-prompt-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt" onclick="
                        navigator.clipboard.writeText('My wallet got drained but I have hostage assets there. Help me rescue them with Kintsugi.');
                        this.classList.add('copied');
                        setTimeout(() => this.classList.remove('copied'), 1400);
                    ">
                        <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor"><path d="M8 2a2 2 0 00-2 2v9a2 2 0 002 2h7a2 2 0 002-2V4a2 2 0 00-2-2H8zm-4 5a2 2 0 00-2 2v9a2 2 0 002 2h7a2 2 0 002-2v-1H8a3 3 0 01-3-3V7H4z"/></svg>
                        <span class="copy-btn-label">Copy</span>
                    </button>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="agent-banner-actions">
                <p class="agent-banner-install-label">Install the skill once:</p>
                <div class="install-box code-block-wrapper">
                    <span class="prompt">$</span>
                    <code id="install-skill-cmd">npx skills add ophelios-studio/skills --skill kintsugi</code>
                    <button type="button" class="copy-btn" aria-label="Copy install command" onclick="
                        navigator.clipboard.writeText('npx skills add ophelios-studio/skills --skill kintsugi');
                        this.classList.add('copied');
                        setTimeout(() => this.classList.remove('copied'), 1400);
                    ">
                        <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor"><path d="M8 2a2 2 0 00-2 2v9a2 2 0 002 2h7a2 2 0 002-2V4a2 2 0 00-2-2H8zm-4 5a2 2 0 00-2 2v9a2 2 0 002 2h7a2 2 0 002-2v-1H8a3 3 0 01-3-3V7H4z"/></svg>
                    </button>
                </div>
                <a href="{$leafBaseUrl}/getting-started/with-an-agent/" class="btn-secondary">
                    See what else to ask
                    <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10.293 3.293a1 1 0 011.414 0l6 6a1 1 0 010 1.414l-6 6a1 1 0 01-1.414-1.414L14.586 11H3a1 1 0 110-2h11.586l-4.293-4.293a1 1 0 010-1.414z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
                </a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <div class="divider-rule"></div>

    {* ─── 6. Open source manifesto ─── *}
    <section class="landing-section landing-section-narrow" id="open">
        <div class="manifesto">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">Our stance</span>
            <h2>
                Open source. No fees. <span class="accent">No upsell.</span>
            </h2>
            <p>
                A wallet rescue tool that charges money in the worst moment of someone's crypto life is a wallet rescue tool taking advantage of panic. We will not do that.
            </p>
            <p>
                Kintsugi is MIT-licensed. The contracts are verified. The library, CLI, and UI are all in one public repository. There is no SaaS tier, no telemetry, no analytics, no signup. Run it yourself, audit every line, pay nothing but your own gas.
            </p>
            <div class="manifesto-meta">
                <a href="{$leafGithubUrl ?? '#'}" class="contract-pill" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
                    <span class="label">Repo</span>
                    <code>github.com/ophelios-studio/kintsugi</code>
                </a>
                <span class="contract-pill">
                    <span class="label">Sepolia rescue</span>
                    <code>0x53c1f40c…21fd5</code>
                </span>
                <span class="contract-pill">
                    <span class="label">Sepolia tracker</span>
                    <code>0x717883ab…47963</code>
                </span>
                <span class="contract-pill">
                    <span class="label">Mainnet</span>
                    <code>pending audit</code>
                </span>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    {* ─── 7. Get started lanes ─── *}
    <section class="landing-section" id="start">
        <span class="section-eyebrow">Three ways forward</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">Where do you want to start?</h2>
        <div class="lanes-row">
            <a href="{$leafBaseUrl}/getting-started/quickstart-cli/" class="lane-card">
                <span class="eyebrow">Right now</span>
                <h3>I'm in trouble. Walk me through a rescue.</h3>
                <p>
                    Five minutes from install to your assets safely sitting in a fresh wallet. Plain language, no Solidity required.
                </p>
                <span class="lane-cta">Start the 5 minute rescue →</span>
            </a>
            <a href="{$leafBaseUrl}/concepts/the-sweeper-problem/" class="lane-card">
                <span class="eyebrow">First</span>
                <h3>I want to understand it before I run it.</h3>
                <p>
                    The sweeper problem, EIP-7702 in plain English, the rescuer wallet pattern, why the rescue is atomic.
                </p>
                <span class="lane-cta">Read the concepts →</span>
            </a>
            <a href="{$leafBaseUrl}/security/threat-model/" class="lane-card">
                <span class="eyebrow">Auditor mode</span>
                <h3>Show me the trust assumptions and contracts.</h3>
                <p>
                    Threat model, what the rescuer can and cannot do, known limits, how to report a vulnerability, links to verified contracts.
                </p>
                <span class="lane-cta">Read the security docs →</span>
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>
</main>
{/block}
